Translation and Build Checklist
- [ ] Rename all FastMCP references to OxFastMCP
- [ ] Use OxCaml (ocaml-variants 5.2.0+ox)
- [ ] Use Jane Street libraries (`core`, `async`, etc.)
- [ ] Use ppx_yojson_conv for JSON (de)serialization
- [ ] Use ppx_compare for comparison functions
- [ ] Reflect all changes in appropriate `dune` files
- [ ] Test-first (ppx_expect + expect_test_helpers_core) with let%expect_test
- [ ] Tests compiled as (library ...) with (preprocess (pps ppx_jane))
- [ ] Create `test_xxx.todo` alongside each new test module
- [ ] For each translated module, create an `xxx.todo` (see structure of `src/exceptions.todo`)

Python→OCaml Module Mapping
- `fastmcp.tools` → `src/tools/`
- `fastmcp.client.client` → `src/client/client.ml`
- `fastmcp.exceptions` → `src/exceptions.ml`
- `fastmcp.tools.tool` → `src/tools/tool.ml`
- `fastmcp.utilities.json_schema` → `src/utilities/json_schema.ml`
- `mcp.types` → `src/mcp/types.ml`

Task Procedure for Each Translation
1. Create `test_xxxx.ml` mirroring the implementation path under `/test/`
2. Add/adjust `dune` with (library ...) and (preprocess (pps ppx_jane))
3. Implement `xxx.ml` using Jane Street style; add ppx_yojson_conv/ppx_compare
4. Create `xxx.todo` in the same directory capturing mappings, gaps, tests, docs, perf, deps

Missing ML Equivalents / Concerns
- Track any Python `from ... import ...` with no OCaml counterpart in the corresponding `xxx.todo`
- Record any semantic differences or limitations introduced in OCaml

Testing Requirements
- Prefer expect tests with small, focused cases
- Cover success paths, error paths, and JSON (de)serialization
- Add integration points for tools/client as needed

Documentation Requirements
- Module docstrings summarizing responsibilities and assumptions
- Keep public APIs explicit and documented

Performance Considerations
- Avoid unnecessary allocations; prefer immutable data and clear boundaries
- Use explicit error handling; avoid broad exception traps

Simple Mindset Principles (to apply during implementation)
- Single responsibility per module/function
- Avoid complecting I/O with business logic
- Prefer pure functions; isolate mutable state when unavoidable
- Be explicit; avoid hidden/magical behavior
- Minimize dependencies; choose constructs that keep artifacts simple

